\abstract{%
	This thesis evaluates the applicability of the coupled SPH--DEM
	(Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics–Discrete Element Method) approach for
	granular dampers mitigating sloshing in ship ballast tanks. A weakly
	compressible SPH formulation was coupled two-way with DEM particles and
	used to perform a parameter study over particle size, fill ratio and
	interaction coefficients.

	A small-scale experimental configuration from literature was
	reproduced; the dominant sloshing frequency differed by \(\approx 17\%\)
	from the reference, consistent with WCSPH time-step constraints.

	Granular dampers reduced peak loads by up to 52\% and increased the effective damping ratio to \(\zeta=0.089\text{--}0.142\). Resonant amplification was
	suppressed by as much as 78\%. The energy budget was collision-dominated
	(61\%), with additional viscous and drag contributions. Sensitivity analysis
	identified restitution (\(S_e=-0.62\)), mass ratio (\(S_m=+0.48\)) and
	friction (\(S_{\mu}=+0.31\)) as the primary factors. Design guidelines
	emerge as \(e<0.5\), particle diameter \(d=4\text{--}6\,\mathrm{mm}\),
	mass ratio 10\text{--}15\% and \(\mathrm{St} \approx 1\).

	We conclude that SPH--DEM is suitable for qualitative and quantitative design
	assessment of granular damping in ballast tanks. Incorporating turbulence and
	enhanced contact-dissipation models, alongside targeted experiments, is likely
	to further improve predictive accuracy.
}

