\section{Granular Dampers: Mechanisms and Evidence}
\label{sec:granulardampers}

Granular dampers, also known as particle dampers, are passive vibration attenuation devices consisting of an enclosure partially filled with solid particles.
When the host structure oscillates, the particles move, collide, and interact with both the container walls and each other, dissipating kinetic energy through inelastic collisions and frictional losses.
Unlike traditional tuned mass or liquid dampers, granular dampers provide broadband energy dissipation, require no active control, and are effective over a wide range of excitation frequencies~\parencite[5716]{prasad2022damping}.

\subsection{Underlying Physical Mechanisms}

Energy dissipation in granular systems arises from several contact-level mechanisms.
During particle impacts, viscous damping in the normal direction removes part of the kinetic energy, while sliding friction in the tangential direction contributes additional losses~\parencite[3379–3380]{zhu2008}.
When particles interact with a surrounding fluid or solid boundaries, viscous forces, including drag and history-dependent terms, further dissipate energy~\parencite[3383]{zhu2008}.
Because these mechanisms are strongly nonlinear and depend on instantaneous contact configurations, Zhu et al. note that such systems have “defied any attempt to model analytically,” rendering closed-form solutions generally infeasible~\parencite[p.~3379]{zhu2008}.
Moreover, even within mathematics, the notion of a ‘closed-form solution’ is not universally defined, which further complicates attempts to obtain analytical expressions for systems governed by discontinuous, path-dependent dynamics.
\subsection{Experimental Investigations}

Experimental studies have established the fundamental performance characteristics
of granular dampers under a variety of vibration conditions.

Experimental studies have established the fundamental performance characteristics of granular dampers under a variety of vibration conditions.
\textcite[p.~3]{avdic2024} investigated the influence of granule size, flowability, and base material on damping performance, showing that these material-dependent parameters strongly affect the dynamic response of the damping element.
Furthermore, \textcite[p.~4]{avdic2024} noted that the measured angle of repose reflects multiple intrinsic properties of the granules, with grain size, particle geometry, and base material all contributing to the observed flowability behaviour.
Their comparison of carbon steel (CS) and polyoxymethylene (POM) fillings demonstrated that although CS granules exhibit higher stiffness due to their material properties, POM-filled dampers can achieve superior overall performance once stiffness and mass effects are taken into account, leading Avdić et al. to conclude that POM is the more promising choice for the studied granular damping element (pp.~10–12).
Building on these insights, \textcite[pp.~1574-1575]{schonleeberhard} performed an extensive
experimental study on a multi-modal host structure and demonstrated that a single
particle damper can simultaneously attenuate several resonance peaks
(60 Hz, 80 Hz, 190 Hz) by up to 90\%. Their results further showed that
particle damping is highly sensitive to vibration amplitude but largely
insensitive to excitation frequency (pp. 1575-1576), and that unlike tuned mass
dampers, particle dampers do not significantly shift the natural frequencies
of the host structure (p. 1575). To quantitatively characterize such broadband
damping behaviour, they introduced two performance metrics—the dynamic influence
factor and the mean influence deviation—which capture how strongly a damper
affects the structural response across frequencies (p. 1576).
\subsection{Numerical Modeling Approaches}

To overcome the limitations of laboratory testing, numerical simulations have been developed to predict granular damping behavior under complex excitation.
The Discrete Element Method (DEM) has emerged as the standard technique for resolving particle-scale motion and contact dynamics~\parencite{cundall1979}.
DEM enables direct computation of individual particle trajectories and energy losses based on Hertz–Mindlin contact mechanics.
However, classical DEM neglects the surrounding fluid and therefore cannot represent the additional damping arising from liquid–particle interactions.

Coupling DEM with Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH) provides a natural extension for capturing these effects~\parencite{liu2022}.
In the coupled SPH--DEM framework, the liquid phase transmits hydrodynamic pressure and viscous drag to the particles, while the granular phase feeds back momentum to the fluid.
This two-way interaction enables realistic modeling of sloshing systems containing granular dampers—an application domain that remains largely unexplored.

\subsection{Parametric Sensitivity and Design Factors}

Granular dampers exhibit strong dependence on particle–particle
interactions, including contact friction, restitution, material contrast
and filling ratio. Higher friction or surface roughness generally increases
energy dissipation through more intense inelastic collisions, although
the resulting internal rearrangements can also lead to changes in the
steady-state packing configuration.

The combined influence of these parameters is highly nonlinear, which
complicates analytical prediction and motivates the parametric analysis
carried out in the present work.

