\subsection{Comparison with Other Damping Technologies}

Granular dampers (GDs) constitute a fundamentally different class of passive damping devices compared to conventional tuned mass dampers (TMDs) and tuned liquid dampers (TLDs). 
Whereas TMDs and TLDs rely on resonance-based energy exchange with the host structure, GDs dissipate vibrational energy through inelastic particle collisions, frictional interactions, and impact-driven momentum transfer within a confined cavity.
As a direct consequence of this mechanism, GDs exhibit an inherently broadband response and maintain effective damping performance over wide frequency ranges without the need for precise tuning or retuning. 
Multiple experimental investigations have confirmed this property, demonstrating attenuation efficiencies exceeding 80--90\% across several structural modes using a single device configuration~\parencite{schonleeberhard}.

In addition to their broadband behaviour, GDs are largely insensitive to environmental and operational variations. 
Because the dissipative mechanism is governed by geometric confinement and particle-scale interactions rather than elastic material properties, GD performance is only weakly affected by temperature fluctuations, humidity, or material aging.
This stands in contrast to TMDs, whose performance is strongly tied to maintaining a narrow tuning ratio, and to TLDs, whose fluid properties introduce sensitivity to temperature and filling ratio.
For TMDs in particular, small deviations of the structural natural frequency from the design point can cause substantial reductions in attenuation performance, making precise tuning and continuous monitoring essential for reliable operation~\parencite[p.~2]{gao2020frequency}.

Despite these advantages, granular dampers also present significant challenges from a design and modelling perspective.
Unlike TMDs and TLDs, for which established analytical and semi-analytical design frameworks exist, GDs currently lack a universally accepted synthesis methodology. 
Their behaviour is governed by highly nonlinear, discontinuous, and history-dependent particle dynamics, making predictive modelling difficult and necessitating extensive parametric testing or computationally intensive discrete-element simulations. 
Recent reviews highlight this absence of standardised design procedures and identify the complex dissipative physics of granular media as a major barrier to wider structural adoption~\parencite{zhu2025}.


\subsection{Synthesis and Implications for the Present Study}

The reviewed studies collectively indicate that granular dampers provide a robust, maintenance-free means of energy dissipation, yet their performance in fluid-coupled environments is insufficiently characterized.
Existing research has largely focused on small-scale, dry experiments and one-way DEM simulations, leaving open questions about their applicability to liquid sloshing conditions relevant to marine ballast tanks.
The present thesis addresses this gap by applying a coupled SPH--DEM modeling framework to investigate how granular dampers interact with liquid sloshing, quantifying their capacity to attenuate free-surface oscillations and reduce dynamic wall pressures.

\section{Sloshing Mitigation in Ballast Tanks}

The strategies reviewed above provide valuable benchmarks for evaluating new damping concepts. Building on this foundation, the present study examines whether a coupled SPH--DEM approach can reproduce and enhance sloshing mitigation in realistic ballast tank configurations.

Partial tank filling induces sloshing, generating dynamic loads~\parencite{krata2013}.

\subsection{Mitigation Techniques}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Baffles:} suppress higher-order sloshing modes~\parencite{konar2023deep}.
	\item Tuned mass dampers (TMDs) — including recent frequency-adjustable designs — have been studied extensively for vibration mitigation of structures under varying dynamic loads~\parencite{gao2020frequency}.  
Tuned liquid dampers (TLDs) remain an active research subject, with new configurations proposed for high-frequency structural vibration control~\parencite{dominizio2024}.

	\item \textbf{Granular Dampers:} simple, passive, and maintenance-free; underexplored under realistic fluid conditions.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Research Limitations}
\begin{itemize}
	\item Limited industrial-scale validation for granular dampers.
	\item Few comparative studies of granular dampers versus TMDs/TLDs under equivalent conditions.
	\item Lack of experimental validation for SPH--DEM models at realistic scales.
\end{itemize}

