\section{Literature Search Strategy and Theoretical Novelty}
\label{sec:litsearch}

The literature review for this thesis was conducted through a systematic and iterative search process between September and January and November~2025.
The primary databases included \textit{Scopus}, \textit{Web of Science}, and \textit{Google Scholar}.
Search queries combined both domain-specific and methodological keywords such as
\textit{``sloshing''}, \textit{``granular damping''}, \textit{``SPH--DEM coupling''}, \textit{``particle dampers''}, \textit{``ballast tank''}, \textit{``free-surface flow''}, and \textit{``multiphase simulation''}.
Boolean operators were applied to refine the searches, which were limited to peer-reviewed journal articles, conference proceedings, and doctoral theses published between 2000 and~2025.

In total, over 120 publications were screened, of which approximately 65 were included in the final synthesis based on methodological quality, relevance, and citation impact.
Priority was given to works that (i) validated the SPH--DEM coupling, (ii) analyzed granular or fluid--particle energy dissipation, or (iii) examined sloshing mitigation in marine or civil structures.
Review papers were used to establish the conceptual landscape, whereas primary research articles were analyzed for specific formulations, parameter studies, and quantitative findings.

All selected sources were critically evaluated in terms of their assumptions, boundary conditions, and reproducibility.
This approach ensured a balanced representation of experimental, analytical, and computational perspectives, avoiding overreliance on any single modeling framework.
The outcome is a coherent theoretical foundation that supports the extension of SPH--DEM modeling to large-scale maritime damping problems.

\subsection*{Theoretical Novelty and Contribution}

From a theoretical standpoint, the novelty of this thesis lies in integrating three previously independent research areas---sloshing hydrodynamics, granular damping physics, and SPH--DEM multiphase modeling---into a unified conceptual and computational framework.
While earlier studies have addressed these topics separately, none have systematically coupled them to model fluid--granular interactions within ballast tanks.
The present work therefore advances the field by:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item demonstrating the feasibility of SPH--DEM coupling for large-scale sloshing conditions,
	\item identifying the dominant parameters governing energy dissipation efficiency, and
	\item establishing a theoretical foundation for experimental validation of hybrid fluid--granular damping systems.
\end{enumerate}

By explicitly articulating this integrative perspective, the study contributes a novel theoretical viewpoint that extends the understanding and predictive modeling of sloshing mitigation using granular dampers.

In summary, this literature review maps the current state of research on granular dampers, SPH--DEM coupling, and sloshing mitigation. The identified gaps—particularly the lack of comprehensive fluid--particle interaction modeling in ballast tank environments—directly motivate the theoretical and methodological developments presented in Chapter~2.

\section{Synthesis and Research Gaps}

Existing studies demonstrate that numerical modeling of sloshing and granular damping has progressed substantially, yet their integration remains limited.
The SPH method has been successfully applied to simulate free-surface deformation and wave impact processes~\parencite{huadams2006}.
DEM-based approaches, in turn, accurately represent inelastic collisions and frictional energy loss among particles~\parencite{zhu2008}.
Recent comprehensive reviews emphasize the maturity and current challenges of SPH methods for multiphase and free-surface flows~\parencite{letouzecolagrossi2025}.

Although SPH and coupled SPH–DEM models have been shown to reproduce laboratory-scale 
and small engineering test cases effectively, their broader use in large-scale 
simulations remains limited due to their high computational demands and several 
unresolved numerical challenges inherent to the SPH method.~\parencite{xiong2025sphdem} p. 2 
This thesis addresses that gap by developing a coupled SPH--DEM model for granular dampers in partially filled ballast tanks.

