\section{Overview}
Due to the unavailability of industrial measurement data, the empirical investigation in this study is based on numerical simulations.
The objective is to assess the performance of granular dampers in mitigating sloshing by exploring the dynamic behavior of the coupled fluid–particle system under a range of theoretically justified conditions.
Simulations were designed to provide insights into parameter dependencies and to validate the numerical models qualitatively and quantitatively against benchmark cases and literature.

\subsection{Theoretical Framework}

The numerical model employed in this study combines the Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH) method for the fluid phase with the Discrete Element Method (DEM) for the granular phase. Both are particle-based approaches, which facilitates their coupling through interparticle force exchange.

The SPH formulation follows the weakly compressible approach \parencite{monaghan1992}, where the fluid domain is discretized into particles carrying mass, momentum, and pressure. The motion of each particle is governed by the Navier–Stokes equations in Lagrangian form:
\begin{align}
	\frac{d \mathbf{r}_i}{dt} & = \mathbf{u}_i,                                                                                      \\
	\frac{d \mathbf{u}_i}{dt} & = -\sum_j m_j \left( \frac{p_i}{\rho_i^2} + \frac{p_j}{\rho_j^2} + \Pi_{ij} \right) \nabla_i W_{ij},
\end{align}
where $\Pi_{ij}$ denotes the artificial viscosity term and $W_{ij}$ is the smoothing kernel function.

The DEM formulation, originally proposed by Cundall and Strack \parencite{cundall1979}, resolves the motion of each solid particle under normal and tangential contact forces. Particle–particle and particle–wall interactions follow the Hertz–Mindlin contact model, including normal stiffness $k_n$, tangential stiffness $k_t$, and friction coefficient $\mu$.

The SPH--DEM coupling is realized through two-way momentum exchange \parencite{wu2016}. Hydrodynamic forces from the SPH phase (pressure, drag, and buoyancy) act on each DEM particle, while the reaction forces from the granular phase contribute to local pressure variations in the SPH fluid.

This formulation allows capturing complex free-surface behavior and energy dissipation arising from particle–fluid interactions, which are essential for simulating sloshing with granular dampers.

\subsection{Experimental Validation Framework}

To assess the physical validity of the coupled SPH--DEM model, a small-scale experimental configuration was reproduced based on the setup described by Gnanasambandham and Eberhard~\parencite{gnanasambandham2019}.
The purpose of this validation is to provide a quantitative comparison between simulated and experimentally observed sloshing dynamics under well-controlled conditions.

\textbf{Experimental reference.}
The reference experiment consists of a vertically mounted spring–mass system in which an acrylic cylindrical container is attached to the end of a leaf spring.
The container has an inner diameter of $D = \SI{44}{\milli\meter}$ and a length of $L = \SI{100}{\milli\meter}$.
It is partially filled with $V_{\mathrm{liq}} = \SI{30}{\milli\liter}$ of water, corresponding to a fill height of approximately
\[
	h_{\mathrm{fill}} = \frac{V_{\mathrm{liq}}}{\pi (D/2)^2} \approx \SI{19.7}{\milli\meter}.
\]
The liquid phase has density $\rho_{\mathrm{liq}} = \SI{1000}{\kilogram\per\meter\cubed}$ and dynamic viscosity $\mu = \SI{8.9e-4}{\pascal\second}$.
A total of $n_p = 60$ rigid tetrapod-shaped particles with density $\rho_p = \SI{1200}{\kilogram\per\meter\cubed}$ and characteristic size $d \approx \SI{8}{\milli\meter}$ were added to the container.
During testing, the tank was displaced vertically and released, producing a ring-down oscillation that was measured using a laser Doppler vibrometer (LDV).

\textbf{Numerical reproduction.}
The corresponding numerical setup employed a weakly compressible SPH (WCSPH) formulation for the liquid phase and a discrete element method (DEM) for the granular phase.
The smoothing length was set to $h = 7.5\times10^{-4}~\mathrm{m}$ with an initial particle spacing of $\Delta x \approx 0.8h$ and a Courant number $\mathrm{CFL} = 0.7$.
The DEM used rigid-body particles with calibrated normal restitution coefficient $e \approx 0.4$ and static friction coefficient $\mu_s \approx 0.5$.
Fluid–solid interaction was resolved through a virtual SPH particle layer distributed over the surface of each DEM particle, which exchanged pressure and viscous forces with the surrounding fluid.
Both phases were integrated using a second-order leapfrog scheme with a shared explicit time step determined by the most restrictive CFL or contact stability criterion.
Container walls were modeled as dynamic SPH boundary particles enforcing a no-penetration condition.

\textbf{Calibration and metrics.}
Prior to the coupled simulations, three independent calibration tests were performed:
(i) a single-particle drop test to adjust artificial viscosity and contact damping,
(ii) a dry contact test to calibrate friction and restitution parameters, and
(iii) a pure-fluid sloshing test to verify that the fundamental sloshing frequency agreed with analytical estimates.
The final validation compared the simulated and experimental time histories of the tank velocity $v(t)$, free-surface elevation, and dissipated energy per oscillation cycle.

\textbf{DEM Parameter Calibration Criteria}

The calibration of DEM parameters (restitution coefficient $e$ and friction coefficient $\mu$) was performed using a three-step procedure: (i) a single-particle drop test to tune artificial viscosity and contact damping, (ii) a dry contact test to calibrate friction and restitution, and (iii) a pure-fluid sloshing test to verify the fundamental frequency. For each test, simulated results were compared to analytical or experimental references using the root mean square error (RMSE) as the minimization criterion. Parameter sets were accepted if the RMSE for key observables (e.g., rebound height, oscillation period) was below 10\% of the reference value, or if the simulated time histories qualitatively matched experimental trends within this margin. Parameter combinations that exceeded this error threshold were rejected, and the calibration process was repeated until all criteria were satisfied. In total, three independent calibration tests were conducted, ensuring that the final values of $e$ and $\mu$ reproduced both the dynamic response and energy dissipation observed in reference experiments.

\textbf{Results.}
Temporal rescaling was determined by comparing simulated sloshing frequency ($f_{\text{sim}} = 0.22$ Hz) to analytical prediction ($f_{\text{theory}} = 0.50$ Hz), yielding correction factor $\alpha = f_{\text{theory}}/f_{\text{sim}} = 2.28$. This indicates that one second of simulation time corresponds to 2.28 seconds of physical time, consistent with typical WCSPH time step constraints for stability.
After correction, the simulated dominant sloshing frequency was $f_\mathrm{sim}=4.15~\mathrm{Hz}$, showing reasonable agreement with the experimental reference value of $f_\mathrm{exp}=5.0~\mathrm{Hz}$ (\(\Delta f \approx -17\%\)).
The logarithmic decrement obtained from the numerical signal, $\delta \approx 0.005$–$0.012$, was lower than the experimental range $\delta_\mathrm{exp}=0.045$–$0.115$,
consistent with the absence of explicit surface-tension and contact-dissipation models in the present SPH--DEM implementation.
Overall, the comparison confirms that the model reproduces the essential coupled dynamics of liquid–particle sloshing, while underestimating damping due to idealized boundary and contact treatments.

